benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/customFields - Remove custom fields from bundle

covered: Valid deletion operations: removing all fields, single field, and multiple fields (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05, TC18).
Non-existent resource and empty-database scenarios: 404 when bundle not found (TC07, TC23).
Input validation: invalid bundleId format (TC06), invalid/empty customField UUIDs (TC09, TC19, TC22), empty customField value (TC19).
Query parameter handling and robustness: multiple customField parameters, extra parameters ignored (TC03, TC11).
Authorization and authentication: missing header (TC08) and invalid/expired tokens (TC13).
Error flows and degraded services: 503/504 when service unavailable or degraded (TC12, TC24).
Regression and data integrity: unrelated bundles unaffected (TC17) and post-removal data consistency (TC25).
Edge cases and performance: boundary header lengths (TC20, TC21) and performance constraint (TC15).
Integration considerations: service degradation and cross-service impact (TC24, TC25).
gaps: Soft-delete semantics: no explicit tests for marking custom fields as deleted vs. removed (if applicable).
Rate limiting: no tests covering throttling or rate-limiting behavior under burst DELETE requests.
Caching behavior: no tests validating caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) for DELETE responses.
Authorization parity: missing test expecting 401/403 for missing credentials (adjust TC08 expectation to align with guidelines).
Idempotency and repeated-DELETE handling: not explicitly tested beyond single/dual concurrent requests (could add explicit repeated-DELETE idempotency test).
recommendations: Align missing-header test expectations with authorization guidelines (expect 401/403).
Add rate-limiting and caching-header tests for DELETE responses.
Add an explicit idempotency test: performing DELETE multiple times on same fields should remain 204 with predictable effects.
Introduce a soft-delete semantics check if the domain uses soft Deletes for bundles or fields.
Automate pagination/large datasets handling if future endpoints expose pagination (not needed here but prepare for scale).
